## Mechanism consistent with ALL constraints

### A. Why â€œclean at write, collapsed at drawâ€ (RenderDoc deterministic)

Your unlock probe reads **`s_lastLockedSliceCPUPtr` before `Unmap`** â€” that is the CPU mapping of the slice that was just written. RenderDoc at eid 2497 shows **IA-fetched inputs** at draw time. If those differ, only three classes remain (given serialization + isolation dead):

| Class | Fits? |
|-------|-------|
| Async CPU/GPU race | **No** â€” serialization dead; collapse is in capture |
| Skin math wrong | **No** â€” engine-side replicate of `fillVertexBuffer` clean |
| **Wrong IA byte offset / wrong bind path at draw** | **Yes** |
| **Slice bytes overwritten after `Unmap` before `DrawIndexed`** | **Possible on shared ring across other work, not within same SBSSP prepareâ†’draw pair** |

Within `ShaderPrimitiveSorter::Phase::draw()`, for one primitive the order is strictly:

```725:781:src/engine/client/library/clientGraphics/src/shared/ShaderPrimitiveSorter.cpp
shaderPrimitive.prepareToDraw();   // lock/write/unlock + setVertexBufferVector
// ...
shaderPrimitive.draw();          // applyPreDrawState â†’ IASetVertexBuffers â†’ DrawIndexed
```

So **no other primitiveâ€™s `lock()` runs between this garmentâ€™s `unlock()` and its `DrawIndexed`**. Overwrite of *this* slice in that window is not the sorter path.

That pushes the collapse to **`applyPreDrawState` binding a different byte band than the slice that was written** â€” i.e. **`ms_currentVBVectorOffsets[0]` at draw â‰  `m_offset Ã— stride` from the write**.

### B. Why the tail is â€œ25 good, 98 identicalâ€

That pattern is characteristic of:

```text
GPU slot i  reads  ring byte  (bindOffset + i Ã— stride)
```

If **`bindOffset = writeOffset + 25 Ã— stride`** (off by +25 verts):

- Slots 0â€“24 show garment verts 25â€“49 â†’ still plausible robe geometry.
- Slots 25+ read from bytes that may be **unwritten ring tail, next writer, or a repeated UI vertex** â†’ one position replicated ~98 times after WVP.

The collapsed post-WVP value Ã—4096 â‰ˆ integers strongly suggests **one specific replicated source vertex**, not NaN garbage â€” consistent with **reading into a quad/fan/degenerate writer**, not random memory.

### C. Why per-buffer isolation didnâ€™t help

Dead end #5 bound per-slice buffers â€œat both bind sitesâ€ and still saw the same spikes. That is expected if the failure is:

- **Stale / wrong offset in `Direct3d11_StateCache` shadow state**, or
- **Vector vs single-stream path flip** (`setVertexBuffer` clears `ms_currentVBVectorActive`; `setVertexBufferVector` clears `ms_currentVBValid`),

not â€œanother consumer discarded my shared ring.â€

**Important diagnostic gap:** your draw probe only fires on **`ms_currentVBValid && ms_currentVBStride == 48`**:

```3233:3253:src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp
if (ms_currentVBValid && ms_currentVBStride == 48 && ...)
```

SBSSP uses **`setVertexBufferVector`**, which sets **`ms_currentVBValid = false`**. The garment draw probe likely **never logged the actual bind used for the spiking draw**. You may have been comparing write offset 2670 against a non-garment single-stream draw.

### D. Why â€œfewer discards = worse; more discards = protectiveâ€

This is the CONSULT-20 paradox, still real, but it explains **scene-wide tearing**, not necessarily this garmentâ€™s clean-unlock capture:

- **Baseline:** `ms_used += requested` â†’ CuiLayer charges ~2 MB per lock â†’ ~370 `WRITE_DISCARD`/frame â†’ driver rename pool accidentally limits reuse collisions.
- **D3D9-faithful accounting:** `ms_used` stays low â†’ CuiLayer gets a **giant `WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE` map** â†’ more bytes nominally â€œappendableâ€ while **deferred draws from earlier in the frame still reference earlier bands** â†’ **worse** tearing (not better).

That does **not** contradict clean-at-unlock for *this* draw; it explains why ring-lifetime â€œfixesâ€ felt like the right family but failed or regressed.

### E. Why serialization didnâ€™t help

If collapse is **already visible in RenderDoc at the draw event**, the GPU is reading bad bytes **deterministically at bind time**, not â€œsometimes racing.â€ Full-frame `Flush`+`GetData` wonâ€™t fix wrong `IASetVertexBuffers` offset/path.

